# /etc/qubes/policy.d/30-mcp-control.policy
# Stages A + B + C + D + E1 — sandbox with dom0-mediated lifecycle, exec,
# file copy, tag-scoped firewall control, cloning, and device attach/detach
# between ai-managed qubes.
# Source of truth: /home/user/qubes_mcp/CLAUDE.md on mcp-control.
# MCP server NEVER edits this file. Operator-installed in dom0.
#
# Evaluation: first-match-wins across all files in /etc/qubes/policy.d/.
# Ordering inside THIS file:
#   1. ALLOW block  (Stages A + B + C + D + E1 surface)
#   2. EXPLICIT DENIES  (documented dangerous methods)
#   3. CATCH-ALL DENY  (default-deny backstop for mcp-control)
#
# The catch-all is load-bearing — do not move any allow line below it.

# =========================================================================
# ALLOW BLOCK
# =========================================================================

# --- Stage A: custom dom0 RPC services (lifecycle, discovery, properties).
# Lifecycle (start/shutdown/kill/pause/unpause/remove) routes through
# qmcp.LifecycleAIManaged rather than the tag-scoped admin.vm.* surface.
# Reason: qrexec's `@tag:` selector does not match klass=DispVM targets
# on at least Qubes R4.3 — the wrapper does the ai-managed check in
# dom0 with qubesadmin authority instead, giving uniform behaviour
# across all klasses.

qmcp.ListAIManagedQubes      *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow
qmcp.SpawnAIManagedQube      *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow
qmcp.GetPropertyAIManaged    *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow
qmcp.SetPropertyAIManaged    *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow
qmcp.LifecycleAIManaged      *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow

# --- Stage B: command execution and file transfer inside ai-managed qubes.
# qmcp.RunInAIManaged and qmcp.CopyToAIManaged are services installed in
# ai-managed templates (NOT dom0) — they execute in the target qube as root.

qmcp.RunInAIManaged          *  mcp-control      @tag:ai-managed  allow  user=root
qmcp.CopyToAIManaged         *  mcp-control      @tag:ai-managed  allow  user=root

# Allow qubes.Filecopy directly between ai-managed qubes (skip operator popup).
# Source AND target both tagged ai-managed; nothing crosses out of the sandbox.

qubes.Filecopy              *  @tag:ai-managed  @tag:ai-managed  allow

# --- Stage C: per-qube firewall rule management on ai-managed qubes.
# target=@adminvm routes the call to dom0 (firewall rules live in dom0's
# qubes.xml; the firewall VM enforces them via iptables on its boot/reload).
# The tag-scoped source-or-rather-argument means AI can only read/write
# rules for qubes carrying ai-managed. Untagged qubes are invisible at the
# firewall surface, matching the lifecycle/property surfaces.

admin.vm.firewall.Get       *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.firewall.Set       *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.firewall.Reload    *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm

# --- Stage D: clone an ai-managed qube into a new ai-managed qube.
# qmcp.CloneAIManagedQube force-tags the clone in dom0 using the same
# atomic + rollback pattern as qmcp.SpawnAIManagedQube. Source-tag check
# happens inside the script; the policy only routes the call to dom0.

qmcp.CloneAIManagedQube      *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow

# --- Stage E1: device attach/detach between ai-managed qubes.
# Attach/Detach route through qmcp wrappers because both endpoints must
# be ai-managed (the wrapper does the tag check on backend AND frontend
# in dom0 with qubesadmin authority — qrexec policy can only gate one
# side of the call). The wrappers shell out to qvm-device under the
# hood, which absorbs the DeviceAssignment-API drift across Qubes 4.1
# → 4.2 → 4.3.
#
# Read-only enumeration (List, Available) is tag-scoped at the policy
# layer directly — pure dom0 admin reads, same pattern as Stage C's
# admin.vm.firewall.Get. Untagged backends fall through to the
# explicit-deny block below (which still lists the Attach/Detach
# methods, denied for any direct caller bypassing the wrapper).

qmcp.AttachDeviceAIManaged       *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow
qmcp.DetachDeviceAIManaged       *  mcp-control  @adminvm         allow

admin.vm.device.block.List       *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.block.Available  *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.usb.List         *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.usb.Available    *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.mic.List         *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.mic.Available    *  mcp-control  @tag:ai-managed  allow  target=@adminvm

# --- System service allows ---
# Background qubes-core-agent services that any normal qube needs to
# function (time sync, app menu updates, notifications, icons). All target
# dom0 (@adminvm); all are read/notification-only — AI cannot exploit them
# via MCP tools because no tool wraps qubes.* services. Allowed without an
# `ask` dialog because they fire frequently in the background and prompting
# the operator on each would be unworkable.

qubes.GetDate                   *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow
qubes.GetImageRGBA              *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow
qubes.WaitForSession            *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow
qubes.SyncAppMenus              *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow
qubes.NotifyTools               *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow
qubes.NotifyUpdates             *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow

# --- Operator UX allows ---
# Without these, the human operator can't perform normal Qubes workflows
# (file copy out, USB attach, clipboard, open-in-VM) from inside mcp-control,
# because the catch-all DENY at the bottom of this file blocks every
# unlisted call. Each line uses `ask` so dom0 shows a confirmation dialog
# per action — the human is always in the loop.
#
# AI cannot exploit these: no MCP tool wraps qubes.* services, and the
# stdio-via-SSH transport doesn't expose an interactive shell. The dialogs
# would surface any AI attempt anyway.

qubes.Filecopy                  *  mcp-control  @anyvm        ask
qubes.OpenInVM                  *  mcp-control  @anyvm        ask
qubes.OpenURL                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm        ask
qubes.ClipboardCopy             *  mcp-control  @anyvm        ask
qubes.ClipboardPaste            *  mcp-control  @anyvm        ask

# USB attach to mcp-control itself (the typical case for the human at
# the terminal). Attaching to OTHER qubes from mcp-control falls through
# to the explicit deny below.
#
# Two services are involved: the Admin API gate (admin.vm.device.usb.*)
# AND the data-plane service (qubes.USB) that carries the actual USB
# stream between sys-usb and the consuming qube. Both must be allowed.
admin.vm.device.usb.Attach      *  mcp-control  mcp-control   ask    target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.usb.Detach      *  mcp-control  mcp-control   ask    target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.usb.Available   *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow  target=@adminvm
admin.vm.device.usb.List        *  mcp-control  @adminvm      allow  target=@adminvm
qubes.USB                       *  mcp-control  sys-usb       ask

# =========================================================================
# EXPLICIT DENIES — documented; the catch-all below would cover these too,
# but listing them explicitly makes intent visible to anyone auditing.
# =========================================================================

# Policy management — AI must never read or rewrite policy.
policy.Get                       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
policy.GetFiles                  *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
policy.List                      *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
policy.Replace                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
policy.RegisterArgument          *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
policy.UnregisterArgument        *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
policy.EvalSimulate              *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
policy.EvalGUI                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Pool & volume manipulation — could overwrite filesystems or exfiltrate.
admin.pool.List                  *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.pool.Info                  *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.pool.Add                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.pool.Remove                *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.pool.volume.Import         *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.volume.Import           *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.volume.CloneFrom        *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.volume.Revert           *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.volume.Clear            *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Backup execution — bulk exfiltration vector.
admin.backup.Execute             *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.backup.Info                *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Direct creation / clone — denied; AI uses qmcp.SpawnAIManagedQube / qmcp.CloneAIManagedQube.
admin.vm.Create.AppVM            *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Create.StandaloneVM     *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Create.TemplateVM       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Create.DispVMTemplate   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.CreateDisposable        *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Clone                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Tag mutation — denied always.
admin.vm.tag.Set                 *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.tag.Remove              *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Property read/write — denied direct; AI uses qmcp.{Get,Set}PropertyAIManaged.
admin.vm.property.Get            *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.property.GetAll         *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.property.Set            *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.property.Reset          *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.property.Help           *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.property.List           *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Lifecycle — denied direct; AI uses qmcp.LifecycleAIManaged.
# Stage D moved lifecycle into a dom0 wrapper because qrexec's @tag:
# selector doesn't reach klass=DispVM targets on Qubes R4.3 (the wrapper
# does the ai-managed check in dom0 with qubesadmin authority instead).
admin.vm.Start                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Shutdown                *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Kill                    *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Pause                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Unpause                 *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Remove                  *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Feature read/write — denied entirely. Wrapped in Stage F.
admin.vm.feature.Get             *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.feature.Set             *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.feature.Remove          *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.feature.List            *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.feature.CheckWithTemplate  *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Firewall — Stage C allows tag-scoped above; the catch-all below still
# refuses untagged targets, so no explicit deny needed here.

# Device API
#  - block/usb/mic: Stage E1 wraps Attach/Detach via qmcp; List/Available
#    are tag-scoped allows above. The Attach/Detach denies here catch any
#    direct caller that bypasses the wrapper (the tag-scoped reads above
#    already make the list/available denies unreachable, so they are
#    omitted to keep the deny block honest about what it still gates).
#  - pci: stays fully denied — PCI passthrough has a different trust
#    model (requires no_strict_reset, qube reboot, dom0-side risk
#    assessment) and is out of Stage E scope. A future stage may wrap it.
admin.vm.device.pci.Attach       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.pci.Detach       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.pci.List         *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.pci.Available    *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.block.Attach     *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.block.Detach     *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.mic.Attach       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.mic.Detach       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.usb.Attach       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.device.usb.Detach       *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Global discovery — denied to enforce invisibility.
admin.vm.List                    *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.Stats                   *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.label.List                 *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.label.Get                  *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.label.Index                *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.Events                     *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Volume info/resize — denied. Not currently surfaced by any stage; a
# future stage may wrap these tag-scoped for AI-visible disk-pressure
# diagnostics, but the current rollout has no need.
admin.vm.volume.List             *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.volume.Info             *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.volume.Resize           *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# Tag reads — denied direct (qmcp.ListAIManagedQubes is canonical discovery).
admin.vm.tag.Get                 *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
admin.vm.tag.List                *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny

# =========================================================================
# CATCH-ALL DENY — default-deny backstop for mcp-control.
# =========================================================================

*  *  mcp-control  @anyvm  deny
